    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1969-05-23T14:22:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1969-05-23T14:22:00-05:00" n="22"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d22">
                <head>22. Telegram 7699 From the Mission to the Organization for Economic
                    Cooperation and Development to Secretary of State <persName corresp="#p_RWP1"
                        >Rogers</persName> in New Delhi<note n="1" type="source" xml:id="d22fn1"
                        >Source: National Archives, <gloss target="#t_RG1">RG</gloss> 59, Central
                        Files 1967–69, <gloss target="#t_AID1">AID</gloss> 9 INDIA. Limited Official
                        Use; Priority. Joint State/<gloss target="#t_AID1">AID</gloss> message.
                        Repeated to the Department of State. The consortium of governments and
                        institutions organized to provide development assistance to India met in
                        Paris, May 22–23, under the chairmanship of the World Bank. The meeting was
                        attended by representatives of Belgium, Canada, Denmark, France, Germany,
                        Italy, Japan, the Netherlands, Sweden, the United Kingdom, and the United
                        States. The International Monetary Fund sent observers.</note>
                    <note n="2" type="summary" xml:id="d22fn2">The telegram reported the results of
                        the India consortium meeting, May 22–23.</note>
                </head>
                <dateline>
                    <placeName>Paris</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                        when="1969-05-23T19:22:00+00:00">May 23, 1969, 1922Z</date>
                </dateline>
                <list type="subject">
                    <head>Subject:</head>
                    <item>India Consortium: Summary</item>
                </list>
                <list>
                    <label>1.</label>
                    <item>Summary of consortium meeting for use as appropriate by Secretary.
                        Detailed reports follow septels:</item>
                    <label>2.</label>
                    <item>Tone of meeting constructive with much laudatory comment on recent
                        improvements in Indian economy and constructive exchange on need for
                        improved Indian performance industrial efficiency, long-term export
                        promotion, decision making re investments, and family planning. Agreement
                        reached for meeting on this subject when <gloss target="#t_UN1">UN</gloss>
                        study complete, purpose to coordinate consortium country efforts with Indian
                        needs.</item>
                    <label>3.</label>
                    <item>
                        <gloss target="#t_AID1">AID</gloss> plans <gloss target="#t_IFY1"
                            >IFY</gloss> 1969–70: Most countries were not in a position to make firm
                        commitments, but expressed intentions (subject in most cases including
                            <gloss target="#t_US1">US</gloss> to legislation) appeared to come
                        fairly close to <gloss target="#t_IBRD1">IBRD</gloss>-recommended level of
                        $1 billion including debt relief. <gloss target="#t_US1">US</gloss>
                        indicated budget request for India in <gloss target="#t_US1">US</gloss>
                        <gloss target="#t_FY1">FY</gloss> 1970 <gloss target="#t_AID1">AID</gloss>
                        bill was $385 million. Japanese and Italians remain reluctant to undertake
                        commitments, latter expressing interest in whether Bank would agree that
                        supplier credits are in some cases appropriate <pb facs="d22-02" n="2"
                            xml:id="d22-02"/> substitute for aid. Germany expressly agreed to ease
                        aid terms and Netherlands and Belgium noted possibility similar
                        action.</item>
                    <label>4.</label>
                    <item>Debt relief: Agreement reached for <gloss target="#t_IFY1">IFY</gloss>
                        1969–70 debt rescheduling in some cases, including US, subject to reference
                        to capitols, and for principle that similar relief should be given in
                        1970–71. <list>
                            <label>A.</label>
                            <item>Amount to comprise at least $300 million over course of three
                                years meaning countries with shortfall in 1968–69 will attempt make
                                full share. Japan to report its contribution in two months: other
                                members indicated compliance.</item>
                            <label>B.</label>
                            <item>Some improvement in terms of rescheduling by Germany while France,
                                Japan and Italy still unable to meet desired terms although latter
                                two will come up to quantitative quota.</item>
                            <label>C.</label>
                            <item>Pressed on subject <gloss target="#t_Sov1">Sov</gloss> bloc debt,
                                    <gloss target="#t_GOI1">GOI</gloss> asserted that it now repeat
                                now has trade deficit with “rupee area” and that it continues apply
                                pressure on <gloss target="#t_USSR1">USSR</gloss> for increased net
                                flow resources in form larger non-project imports, with some
                                success.</item>
                            <label>E.</label>
                            <item>India pressed hard by several delegations, including <gloss
                                    target="#t_US1">US</gloss>, to limit use supplier
                                credits.</item>
                        </list>
                    </item>
                    <label>5.</label>
                    <item>Indian del highly pleased with results consortium meeting and tell us they
                        are so reporting to Delhi.</item>
                </list>
                <closer>
                    <signed>Brown</signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
